result.execSummary:
Brandon G. Swartz was extradited to another county, state or jurisdiction. Extradition means Brandon G. Swartz was accused or convicted of an offense in another county, state or jurisdiction and was taken there to face their charge(s) or conviction.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.descr: Records of prosec. are converted data. See file.

records.addlTxt: Defendant Brandon G. Swartz in court, in custody.  Sue Mueller appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  DE states he has dyslexia so he can't read the complaint.  Recess for court security to read documents to the DE.  Back on the record, the Court questions DE on documents being read to him.  DE agrees all documents were read to him.  Defendant waives reading of complaint.  Advised rights to an attorney.  Court then proceeds to extradition matter from the state of Mississippi.  DE is agreeing to extradition.  Court questions DE on that waiver of extradition/accepts/waiver and parties sign all documents.
